Model: Linear Regression

Linear Regression Model

In this section, our focus narrows to the intricacies of the linear regression model, with the dual objectives of discerning whether a playerâs Actions Per Minute (APM) can be accurately predicted and identifying the pivotal features that most significantly influence the prediction of a playerâs APM.

df$Age<-as.numeric(df$Age)
df$HoursPerWeek<-as.numeric(df$HoursPerWeek)
df$TotalHours<-as.numeric(df$TotalHours)

#sum(is.na(df$Age))
#there are about 185 missing value in total, about 55 players, so omit
#3395 originally, 3338 after omit, deleted 57 observations--reasonable due to small amount
df<-na.omit(df)

#####remove game ID cuz it's not important
df <- df %>% select(-GameID)

set.seed(2333)  
split <- sample.split(df$APM, SplitRatio = 0.8)
training <- subset(df, split == TRUE)
testing <- subset(df, split == FALSE)
df2_cor<-cor(training)

#png(filename="correlation_plot_large.png", width=1200, height=1200, res=120)
corrplot(df2_cor,method="circle",order="hclust",tl.col="black")

The correlation plot revealed striking relationships: âActionLatencyâ and âGapBetweenPACsâ exhibited a notable positive correlation, while âNumberOfPACsâ and âLeagueIndexâ inversely correlated with âActionLatency.â These early insights suggested key areas of focus for our predictive modeling.

For the initial model, we included all available predictors. However, upon scrutinizing the modelâs summary, we identified several predictors like âHoursPerWeekâ, and âTotalHoursâ that lacked statistical significance, hence presenting an opportunity to refine our model.

Predictive Capacity

predictions <- predict(model, newdata = testing)

# Actual values
actuals <- testing$APM

# Compute errors
errors <- predictions - actuals
MAE <- mean(abs(errors))
MSE <- mean(errors^2)
RMSE <- sqrt(MSE)

# Print the metrics
cat("MAE:", MAE, "\nMSE:", MSE, "\nRMSE:", RMSE)
MAE: 5.528712 
MSE: 87.58362 
RMSE: 9.358612

Optimal Linear Regression Model

###process the data 

training1<-training%>%
  select(-GapBetweenPACs,-LeagueIndex,-HoursPerWeek,-TotalHours,-AssignToHotkeys,-UniqueHotkeys,-GapBetweenPACs,-TotalMapExplored,-ComplexUnitsMade)
best_fit<-lm(APM~.,data=training1)
pred<-predict(best_fit,newdata=testing)
real<-testing$APM

errors <- pred-real
MAE <- mean(abs(errors))
MSE <- mean(errors^2)
RMSE <- sqrt(MSE)

cat("MAE:", MAE, "\nMSE:", MSE, "\nRMSE:", RMSE)

Conclusion

Considering the scale of APM, the predictive metric RMSE at around 9.357 means that linear regression model may not be the optimal choice for predicting playerâs APM.

The most important features in predicting a playerâs APM include:

  1. Age

  2. SelectByHotkeys

  3. MinimapRightClicks

  4. NumberOfPACs

  5. ActionLatency

  6. ActionsInPAC

  7. WorkersMade

  8. ComplexAbilitiesUsed
